@c *********************************************************************
@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction

Dezyne is a component based language, as well as a method for the
development of event-driven systems.  The language has formal semantics,
which is coherently expressed in: a textual representation, a graphical
representation, a mathematical representation, a source code
representation, and the observable behaviour of a machine executing the
resulting program.  The concepts available in the language denote the
different properties@footnote{ Structural: events and their direction in
an interface, ports on a component, components in a system, bindings
between the ports; behavioural: guarded trigger => action | assignment |
if-else | function} that can be observed and have meaning in one or more
of the reprentations: textual, graphical, mathematical, program and
execution.

@menu
* Purpose::                     Why are we creating Dezyne?
* Principles::                  Guiding design principles.
* Typical use of Dezyne::       The sweet spots.
* The Dezyne Application Domain::  The bigger picture.
@end menu

@node Purpose
@section Purpose

The purpose of Dezyne is to eliminate the need for testing certain
aspects or qualities of a software program that could instead be proven
to be correct by applying formal verification methods.

@node Principles
@section Principles

Dezyne aims to support known software engineering principles:
@itemize
@item
clarity and ease of discovery
@itemize
@item
visual overview of architecture (layers of decomposition)
@item
visual overiew of behaviour (event trace scenarios)
@end itemize
@item
rigor and formality
@itemize
@item
Dezyne allows enforcing completeness and correctness
@item
implementations consistent with specifications
@item
specification consistency
@end itemize
@end itemize
@itemize
@item
separation of concerns (divide and conquer, low coupling -- high
cohesion)
@itemize
@item
data is separated from control
@item
components allow for functional decomposition
@item
interfaces specify the conversations between each peer in a point to
point relation
@end itemize
@end itemize
@itemize
@item
composition is separated from behaviour
@end itemize
@itemize
@item
modularity (low coupling, high cohesion; dependency inversion)
@itemize
@item
at the file level, Dezyne allows separating type, interface,
component and system definitions
@item
a component only depends on its interfaces
@item
a system only depends on it components
@item
a system is a component
@end itemize
@item
abstraction (Liskov substitution)
@itemize
@item
data independence
@item
an event represents the transition from one (system) state to
another
@item
its name and place in the system structure strongly indicates
its meaning
@item
an interface is the complete abstraction of an implementation
from the perspective of any client
@item
and interfaces completely isolate the implementation from its
environment
@end itemize
@item
anticipation of change (open closed)
@itemize
@item
modularity and composition allows changing implementations
whithout changing interfaces, dependencies and dependents
@item
a system in Dezyne is inherently protected from changes
propagating@footnote{Interfaces are like a change firewall, they stop a
change propagating across modules.}
@end itemize
@item
generality
@itemize
@item
Dezyne allows trivially substituting components offering a
port of a compatible interface type
@item
Dezyne's data independence@footnote{Data types in Dezyne are similar to typedefs in
C and allow a component to be repurposed without changes to the model
itself.} allows components to be more general
@end itemize
@item
incremental development
@itemize
@item
increments in Dezyne can obviously follow component scope
@item
Dezyne supports use case driven development or cross-cutting
features equally well
@end itemize
@item
testability
@itemize
@item
trace generation allows for 100% test coverage of code paths
@end itemize
@end itemize

