@node The Dezyne Modeling Language
@chapter The Dezyne Modeling Language

When a software system is built, it is good practice to split it up
(decompose) in parts that have high cohesion and low coupling.  High
cohesion means that the system part performs a dedicated task or
responsibility.  Low coupling means that the system parts are able to
perform their responsibility without much interaction with other parts,
system parts thus have simple interfaces to interact with each other.

@menu
* System Decomposition::
* Creating an Interface::
* Creating a Component::
* Using Local Variables::
* Using Data Variables and Parameters::
* Specifying Behaviour::
* Decomposing a Component::
@end menu

@node System Decomposition
@section System Decomposition

As an illustration, below a picture of a system with four parts where
the loader loads raw input into a machine, the processor transforms the
raw input into the final product and the output part moves the product
out of the machine and the complete process is controlled by the
controller.

@example
                         [controller]
                              |
         ---------------------------------------------
         |                    |                      |
     [loader]            [processor]             [output]
@end example

Software development using Dezyne is component based, meaning that the
system parts are @code{component}s.

@itemize
@item
A component implements a certain functionality.
@item
A component implementation may use the functionality offered by other
components.
@item
The functionality that is offered by a component to others is defined in
the component's @code{interface}.
@item
The functionality of a component can be used by sending and receiving
@code{event}s to and from the @code{component} over the
@code{interface}, which is similar to calling one or more methods on the
component interface.
@end itemize

To illustrate this, in the interaction diagram below the component
called @code{application} requests the component @code{protocol_stack}
to activate itself by sending the @code{enable} event to the
@code{protocol_stack} component.  The protocol_stack responds
synchronously with a @code{reply}, either a void reply or a value
returned as result of the @code{enable}.

@example
 [application]     [protocol_stack]
      |                     |
      |       enable        |
      |-------------------->|
      |      "reply"        |
      |<- - - - - - - - - - |
@end example

Events have a direction.  The direction is determined as seen from the
@code{component} providing the service.  For the @code{protocol_stack}
component in this example the @code{enable} event is an ``in event''.

