@node Synchronous and asynchronous communication
@subsection Synchronous and asynchronous communication

Between components there are two fundamental type of interactions: 1)
synchronous and 2) asynchronous.

The example above depicts a synchronous action, after sending the event
enable to the protocol_stack, the Application execution will be blocked
until the "reply" (either a void reply or a value returned as result) is
received.

When the protocol_stack is activated, it can be requested to setup a
connection by sending the event @code{connect} to it.  After giving a
@code{reply} on this event the protocol_stack component will start
setting up a connection and the two components continue to run
concurrently, i.e., are able to perform other tasks while the connection
request is being processed by the protocol_stack component.  Once the
request is completed the protocol_stack will send a notification
connected to the Application.  This illustrates an asynchronous action.

@example
   [application]     [protocol_stack]
        |                     |
        |     connect         |
        |-------------------->|
        |      "reply"        |
        |<- - - - - - - - - - |
        |                     |
        |                     |
        |                     |
        |    connected        |
        |<--------------------|
        |      "reply"        |
        |- - - - - - - - - - >|
@end example

Remember that events have a direction.  For the protocol_stack component
in this example the connected event is an ``out event''.  The
application, however, receives this event as an in event that has a void
return or some other return type (currently Dezyne only supports void
out events).

@node Interfaces as abstraction of a component's behaviour
@subsection Interfaces as abstraction of a component's behaviour

In the Dezyne Modelling language, an @code{interface} contains the
definition of the events, their direction and optionally their
parameters, and a specification of the externally visible behaviour of
the component that will provide an implementation of the interface.

With behaviour we mean which events (or method calls) can be received
and can be sent at which stages in the execution process, or in other
words the protocol a user of the interface should obey.  In the case of
the Application and protocol_stack the interface defines that the
protocol_stack should first be enabled before anything else can be done
with it, that a connect must be followed by a connected and that
it is not allowed to send a second connect before a connected has
been received.

As described above, components use or provide functionality via
interfaces and not by interacting directly with other
components.  Therefore, interface specifications can not contain
component implementation details.

An interface specification that defines part of the
@code{protocol_stack} interface (the enabling and disabling) in the
example above could look like:

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/iprotocol-stack1.dzn
@end example

In the interface specification events that are not specified in a
particular state are marked ``implicitly illegal'' @footnote{Before
2.14, the user had to specify all @code{illegal} actions accurately and
specifically}.

To unambiguously define all possible behaviour, an interface must
specify all replies that are possible.  Definition of all possible
replies is described in way that is abstract from implementation
details.  What you see specified in the OFF state when the enable event
is received is an example of how this is done in the Dezyne Modeling
language.  What is described here is that as a result of the enable
event two things can happen: a reply plus a state transition in case
enabling is successful and a reply when enabling fails.  In Dezyne this
is referred to as a @dfn{non deterministic choice}.  With this
definition it is clear that for a user of this interface that it should
be able to deal with both replies at this stage.

In the interface above, there is no definition yet the connectionReq and
especially how the connected will be returned in case processing of
the connection request is ready.  How to specify this is outlined next.

@node Modelling events not visible to the outside world but leading to external visible behaviour
@subsection Modelling events not visible to the outside world but leading to external visible behaviour

@i{The following is crucial for understanding how to develop models in Dezyne.}

As mentioned, components use or provide functionality via interfaces and
not by interacting directly with other components.  Therefore, interface
specifications can not contain component implementation details.

However, when this leads to externally visible behaviour, interfaces
necessarily capture decisions that are internal to the
implementation.  As an example consider in the case above the completion
of the connection request that will trigger the server component to
return a notification @code{connected}.  But how is that captured in an
interface specification that should not contain implementation details?

There are two options to specify internal events (like the completion of
the request initiated by @code{connect}), that lead to external events
in interfaces:

@itemize
@item
by using @dfn{on inevitable}; meaning that when nothing else happens and
the system is not triggered externally, the event will eventually always
occur.  For example a timeout event of a timer will eventually always
take place if the timer is not cancelled by the client.
@item
by using @dfn{on optional}; meaning that it may or may not occur.  For
example, an error message may not be generated when the system is
working properly.
@end itemize

