@cindex Creating an Interface
@cindex event

@node Specifying Events
@subsection Specifying Events

Component interaction is performed via so-called @b{@i{events}} through
instances of interfaces (that are called ports).

In each interface therefore the events that can be received (in events)
and sent (out events) are specified.

@menu
* Event Syntax::
* Event Examples::
@end menu

@node Event Syntax
@subsubsection Event Syntax

An event is declared by its direction (@b{in} or @b{out}), type and name.

The direction indicates if the event is received by (in) or sent (out)
from a component that will be implementing the interface

Out events are only allowed to have @b{void} type.

@example
   @b{in} return-type event-name();     // an in event definition
   @b{out} @b{void} event-name();          // an out event definition
@end example

Events can also have a parameter list to pass data variables,
@pxref{Using Data Variables and Parameters},.

@example
[in/out] return-type event-name(parameter-list)
@end example

The parameter list is a set of the following: [in/out/inout] indicating
whether the datatype is input for or output from the event, the
parameter type and parameter name.  See also @ref{Using Data Variables
and Parameters}.

@node Event Examples
@subsubsection Event Examples

@subsubsection An interface with three void events (and a simple behaviour)

The following interface has three events defined: two in events and one
out event.

The direction is as seen from the component implementing this interface.

@example
@b{interface} imotion
@{
  @b{in} @b{void} start();
  @b{in} @b{void} stop();
  @b{out} @b{void} ready();
  @{behaviour@}
  @{
    on start, stop: @{@}
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection An interface with an enum type event

This interface has three events defined: two incoming events and one
outgoing event.  One of the incoming events is of an enum type, that is
defined in the first line of the interface definition.

@example
@b{interface} isimple_protocol
@{
  @b{enum} result @{OK, FAILED, ERROR@};
  @b{in} result connect();
  @b{in} result disconnect();
  @b{behaviour}
  @{
    @b{on} connect: @b{reply}(result.OK);    // Set reply value to 'result.OK'
    @b{on} disconnect: @b{reply}(result.OK); // Set reply value to 'result.OK'
  @}
@}
@end example

