@node Behaviour
@subsection Behaviour

A behaviour section is used to define the actions an interface or
component will perform based on the events received.

@subsubsection Interface Versus Component Behaviour

Behaviour in an interface is a specification.  It is an agreement
between components providing and requiring this interface about the
messages and protocol exchanged.  Both components must adhere to this
specification.  Interface conformance is an imprtant check in the
verifier.  The code generator does not generate any code based on the
behaviour specification of an interface.

Behaviour in a component is a definition.  It defines the actual
behaviour expressed by the object modeled.  Whereas an interface might
still allow some freedom, sometimes multiple messages are allowed,
inside a component the behaviour must be fully deterministic.  The code
generator uses this component behaviour specification to generate target
code.

@subsubsection Syntax

The @code{behaviour} keyword is used to declare a behaviour
section.  Optionally it may have a name.

@example
@{behaviour@} [Optional_Name]
@{
   <behaviour-body>
@}
@end example

The behaviour body contains a collection of statements that define the
actions that will be performed based on events received.

The following elements can be used in the behaviour body:

@itemize

@item Local variables: @pxref{Using Local Variables},
@item Functions: @pxref{Using functions},
@item @pxref{Actions},
@item State definitions and initialisations: @pxref{Specifying Stateful Behaviour},
@item @pxref{Reply},
@item Conditions: @pxref{Using Conditional Statements},
@item Guards: @pxref{Using Guards},
@end itemize

