@node Variable Syntax
@subsection Variable Syntax

Variables are named, have a type, and an initial value, which is an expression:

@example
variableType variableName = initialValue;
@end example

Supported types are:

@itemize

@item @b{enum}: enumerated type.
@item @b{bool}: boolean type (@b{true}, @b{false})
@item @b{subint}: integer type.
@end itemize

To ensure that an integer variable falls within a finite set (in order
to have a limited range of possible paths / states in the system), use a
type definition, e.g., @code{subint int @{0..10@}}.

@node Variable Examples
@subsection Variable Examples

@subsubsection Simple state machine where the state is captured in a variable of enum type

This example shows a simple state machine for a siren where the state is
captured in an enumeration.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/isiren1.dzn
@end example

@subsubsection Simple state machine where the state is captured in a boolean type

This example shows a simple state machine for a siren where the state is
captured in a variable of boolean type

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/isiren2.dzn
@end example

@subsubsection Limited retrying activation of a device using a variable of integer type

This example shows how a counter based on an integer type can be used to
limit retrying activation of a device.

@example
component alarm_system
@{
  provides ialarm alarm;
  requires isensor sensor;
  requires isiren siren;
  behaviour
  @{
    enum status
    @{
      NOT_ACTIVATED,
      ACTIVATED_IDLE,
      ACTIVATED_ALARM,
      DEACTIVATING
    @};
    subint int @{0..10@};                 // int is defined as integer within the range 0-10
    int counter = 0;                    // int is initialised with value 0.
    status state = status.NOTACTIVATED;
    void activating(sensor.values value)  // recursive function to activate the sensor, it will retry 10 times.
    @{
      if (value == sensor.values.OK)
      @{
        reply(alarm.values.OK);
        state = status.ACTIVATED_IDLE;
      @}
      else
      @{
        if (counter <10)
          @{
          counter = counter + 1;
          sensor.values val = sensor.activate();
          activating(val);                 // try again
          @}
        else
          @{
          reply(alarm.values.FAILED);
          @}
       @}
    @}
    [state.NOTACTIVATED]
    @{
      on alarm.switch_on():
      @{
        sensor.values val = sensor.activate();
        activating(val);                    // call the activation function
      @}
    @}
    /* ...  */
    /* ...  */
  @}
@}
@end example

