@node Actions
@subsection Actions

The actions an interface or component should perform when an event is
received are specified within a Behaviour (@pxref{Specifying
Behaviour}).

Actions can be changing the value of a variable, invoking a function,
generating another event or changing to another state and any
combination.

In response to one event trigger, there can be different actions to be
taken as long as they have non-overlapping guards.  Guards are boolean
expressions.  The statement behind the guard is selected when the
expression evaluates to true.  The keyword @code{otherwise} defines a
catch-all guard which is true only when none of the other guard
expressions in a list of @code{guard}s evaluates to true.

Note that the use of guards is reserved for action selection.  The
guards in combination with the trigger event determine which action is
activated.  Thus, the action is a (compound) statement inside an
@code{on} (optionally) behind an innermost guard.

@subsubsection Syntax

Defining an action statement:

@example
@b{on} port1.event(), port.another_event():
@{
  action-body;
@}
@end example

Here @code{port1.event} and @code{port2.anther_event} are event
instances, which refer to port variables @code{port1} and @code{port2}
and to events @code{event} and @code{another_event}.

Intentionally the 'Statement' will be executed when one of the two
triggers occurs.

action-body: a collection of conditions / guards and statements
(function invocations, changing variable values, changing to another
state, setting a reply value, generating another event, marking the
event as illegal) that define what actions to perform.

Defining a guarded action statement:

@example
[state.State1]
on port1.event(), port2.another_event():
@{
  action-body;
@}
@end example

Here the action statement will only be selected when guard
[state.State1] evaluates to true.

Special action statements can defined that will be performed in case no
other events occur, or that optionally may be performed in case no other
events occur, @pxref{Using inevitable and optional}.

