@node Specifying Stateful Behaviour
@subsection Specifying Stateful Behaviour

State variables and guard expressions enable specification of protocols
in a behaviour section.  They specify the selection of one of multiple
different actions.  @xref{Actions} for an input event.

The state of an interface is composed of the values of all its state
variables.

State variables can refer to public types (e.g., defined for use as
event return values) or to private type definitions local to the
'behaviour' section.  Types can be boolean, integer with limited
contiguous range or enumerated.

Guards are boolean expressions based on state variables.  The statement
behind the guard is selected when the expression evaluates to true.  The
keyword @code{otherwise} defines a catch-all guard which is true only
when none of the other guard expressions in a list of @code{guard}s
evaluates to true.

@subsubsection Syntax

Defining a state variable type based on an enum.

@example
enum status @{state1, state2@};
@end example

Defining a state variable based on the above type and initialising it:

@example
status state = status.state1;
@end example

Defining a guarded action statement

@example
[state == status.state1]
@{
  action-statement ;
@}
@end example

or using the @code{field-test} shorthand

@example
[state.state2]
@{
  action-statement ;
@}
@end example

Here the action statement will only be selected when guard
@code{[state.state1]} evaluates to true.

@xref{Actions}, for how to declare action statements.

