@node Reply
@subsection Reply

The @code{reply} keyword assigns a value to be returned.  The
@code{reply} keyword also specifies that a blocked thread is allowed to
return when all statements in the enclosing action block have been
performed.

A 'reply' statement may appear anywhere in an 'action'.  Execution of an
action block continues after a 'reply' statement is performed.  Thread
returns occur when the current execution thread reaches the end of the
current action block.  Then all threads return for which a 'reply' has
been executed in the current action block.

Void 'reply' must be omitted in interface models and in non-blocking
component action statements.  In these cases the void reply is implicit.

@subsubsection Syntax

@example
1) reply(reply-expression);
@end example

@example
2) port-name.reply(); (since 2.0.0)
@end example

@example
3) port-name.reply(reply-expression); (since 2.0.0)
@end example

Explanation:

1) Evaluate @code{reply-expression} and use it to set the reply value.

2) Allow void return on port with name 'port-name'.  (This form applies
to component models when the current 'action' was specified as
'blocking' or when port 'port-name' is still blocked.)

3) Evaluate @code{reply-expression} and use it to a allow valued return
on port with name 'port-name'.

A @code{reply-expression} must be a simple expression and may contain
only one unconditional @code{call} or @code{action} (since 2.14).

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection Setting an enum as reply value.

This example shows how to set a reply value using an enumerated type.

@example
interface inetwork
@{
// interface to the Network.
// The Network can be requested to send a message by using send_message.
// When the message has been sent the Network will inform it's client
// by using message_sent.
  in bool send_message();
  out void message_sent();
  behaviour
  @{
    enum status @{IDLE, BUSY@};
    status state = status.IDLE;
    [state.IDLE]
    // initial or idle status
    @{
      on send_message: // the interface must cover the case that a message is received successfully:
      @{
        reply(true);
        state = state.BUSY;
      @}
      on send_message: // the interface must cover the case that a message is not received successfully:
        reply(false);
    @}
    ...
  @}
@}
@end example

