@node Using illegal
@subsection Using illegal

To specify that an event is not allowed at a certain stage, the keyword
@code{illegal} can be used.

@subsubsection Syntax

The keyword @code{illegal} is used to indicate that an event is not allowed:

@example
@b{on} port1.event(), port2.another_event(): illegal;
@end example

Here @code{port1.event} and @code{port2.anther_event} are event
instances, which refer to port variables @code{port1} and @code{port2}
and to events @code{event} and @code{another_event}.

Note: @b{do not use illegal in conditional statements (if / if else) or
functions in interface definitions} ! This is because an event can only
be declared illegal in a direct way due to the declarative character of
interfaces.  (Or in other words: in an interface one declares the
expected behaviour and an illegal inside conditional statements or
functions would require an evaluation of the conditional statement or
function for the be expected behaviour.)

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection A timer where depending on the state certain events are allowed and others not

This example shows the interface specification for a timer.  Initially a
timer can be created and it is not allowed to cancel the timer before
creation.  When the timer has been created it is not possible to request
again creation of the timer.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/itimer2.dzn
@end example

@subsubsection Incorrect and correct interface definition with a conditional illegal

An interface has to be defined that does not allows a second event
(check_model in this case) before the asynchronous reply (check_done)
has been sent to the first event.

The following code snippet shows an incorrect interface definition with
an illegal inside an if-else construction.

@example
 [state.AUTHENTICATED]
    @{
      on check_model:
      @{
         if (checking_model == false)
         @{
            reply(res.Ok);
            checking_model = true;
         @}
         else illegal;
      @}
      on inevitable:
      @{
          if (checking_model == true)
          @{
              checking_model = false;
              check_done;
          @}
      @}
   @}
@}
@end example

 The following snippet shows how to correctly define this:.

@example
[state.AUTHENTICATED]
@{
      [!checking_model] on check_model:
      @{
          reply(res.Ok);
          checking_model = true;
      @}
      [checking_model] on check_model: illegal;
      [checking_model] on inevitable:
      @{
        checking_model = false;
        check_done;
      @}
@}
@end example

