@node Blocking
@subsection Blocking
(since 2.0.0)

The @code{blocking} keyword allows omission of a @code{reply} from an
action statement and supresses the implicit void reply performed after
the last statement in an action statement.  An action statement in
another port in-event should perform the @code{reply} for the blocked
port.  Thus, time and value of a blocked port reply depend on another
in-event.  The keyword @code{blocking} is allowed to appear once in the
path of statements prefixing an action statement.

Only 'provides' ports are affected by 'blocking'.  A call of a provided
port in-event will not return before a @code{reply} is performed for
that port.

Guard expressions or 'on event' is commutative with respect to
blocking.  If 'blocking' appears before a guard or 'on event' it applies
to the action statement after the guard or 'on event'.

@b{Note:} 'blocking' may only be used in components with a single
'provides' port.  This limitation may be lifted in a future release.

@b{Note:} Systems containing 'blocking' component instances must be
contained in a thread-safe shell (@pxref{Thread-safe Shell}).

@subsubsection Syntax

@example
  on event: blocking action-statement; (1)
@end example

@example
  blocking on event: action-statement; (2)
@end example

@example
  on event: blocking [guard] action-statement; (3)
@end example

@example
  on event: @{blocking [guard] action-statement1; [guard] action-statement2;@} (4)
@end example

Explanation:

2) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the action-statement following 'on
event:'.  This form is semantically equivalent to 1).

3) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the action-statement following
[guard].  This form is semantically equivalent to "on event: [guard]
blocking action-statement;"

4) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to action-statement1.  It does NOT
apply to action-statement2.

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection Thread signalling

component @code{ca} illustrates the use of @code{blocking} to postpone
thread return.  An 'on event' on a different port performs the
@code{reply} statement for the blocked port.

The action statement in @code{on pp.request_value} is marked as
@code{blocking} and does not contain a @code{reply}.  A thread calling
@code{pp.request_reply} blocks after the @code{rp.request()} action.
The blocked thread returns when the action statement for @code{on
rp.accept} or @code{on rp.reject} have been performed.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/ca.dzn
@end example

