@node Integrating Scheme Code
@section Integrating Scheme Code

@quotation Note
The Scheme code generator is still considered experimental, use with
caution.
@end quotation

To enable the Scheme code generator, configure by doing something like

@example
./configure --enable-languages=scheme --with-courage
@end example

Dezyne comes with a code generator for GNU Guile @pxref{,,, guile, Guile
reference manual}.  Scheme is an interesting language for using with
Dezyne.  It supports a functional programming style that can be applied
in handwritten code.

@c Not only is Scheme much friendlier than C or C++ for prototyping
@c (@pxref{Scheme vs C, Why Scheme is More Hackable Than C,, guile, GNU
@c Guile Reference Manual}).

Program code written in a purely functional style is more reasonable
than imperative code and especially so for concurrent programs
(@pxref{Chapter 3,, Modularity Objects and State, sicp, Structure and
Interpretation of Computer Programs}).  The Scheme code for Dezyne
components that is generated by the code generator (@xref{Invoking dzn
code}) can still use assignments to store state in an imperative way,
but that is not a problem as this code is verified: the most tricky
aspects of the software are left to Dezyne!

@menu
* Namespace to Module::
@end menu

@node Namespace to Module
@subsection Namespace to Module

The Scheme code generator introduces the ``namespace to module'' feature
which means that a Dezyne file, when it contains a single namespace, is
assumed to describe a module, such as found in languages like GNU Guile
(@pxref{Modules, Guile modules,, guile, GNU Guile Reference Manual}),
JavaScript (Python, etc.).  Similarly, foreigns are assumed to live in
their own module, so that this module can be used/required/imported.

Things to note:

@itemize

@item
Dezyne files that define more than one namespace are not supported for
``namespace to module'',

@item
foreigns go into their own module,

@item
interfaces used by a foreign need to go into their own Dezyne file to
avoid introducing cyclic dependencies,

@item
avoid the name @code{foreign}, the class @code{<foreign>}

@item
foreigns that use the same interfaces need to form a chain of
@code{use-module} and @code{re-export} their port accessors
(@pxref{Using Guile Modules,,, guile, Guile reference manual}).

@end itemize

