@node Invoking dzn lts
@section Invoking @command{dzn lts}

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}

The @command{dzn lts} command can be used t navigate and query an
@var{lts} in Aldebaran (@code{aut}) format (@xref{Invoking dzn graph},
@xref{Invoking dzn traces}).

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} lts @var{option}@dots{} [@file{FILE}]@dots{}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --deadlock
@itemx -d
Detect deadlock in @var{lts} (after failures introduction).

@item --deterministic
Detect non-determinism in @var{lts} with respect to all labels.

@item --exclude-illegal
Remove edges leading to illegal (in combination with --failures).

@item --failures
@itemx -f
Introduce a failure for each 'optional' event.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn lts}, and then exit.

@item --illegal
@itemx -i
Detect whether lts contains @code{<illegal>} labels.

@item --list-accepts
@itemx -a
List acceptance sets for state reachable by @var{trace}.

@item --list-events
@itemx -e
List event alphabet (edge labels) for each @var{file}.

@item --livelock
@itemx -l
Detect tau-loops in @var{lts}.

@item --metrics
@itemx -m
Number of states and number of transitions.

@item --deterministic-labels=@var{label}[,@var{label}@dots{}]
@itemx -n @var{label}[,@var{label}@dots{}]
Assert determinism by detecting multiple edges of @var{label} from a
single state.

@item --prefix=@var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
@itemx -p @var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
Find states reachable by @var{event}s.  The default is: empty trace =>
initial state.

@item --tau=@var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
@itemx -t @var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
Hide all @var{event}s.

@item --single-line
@itemx -s
Report an error including trace on a single line.

@item --validate
@itemx -v
Validate Aldebaran (@var{aut}) files.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn parse
@section Invoking @command{dzn parse}

The @command{dzn parse} command parses a Dezyne file and reports any
errors, both syntax errors as Well-formedness (@xref{Well-formedness})
errors.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} parse @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --preprocess
@itemx -E
Resolve imports imports and produce content stream.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn parse}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --list-models
List the Dezyne models defined in the file, with their type.

@item --locations
@itemx -L
Show locations in output @var{ast}.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Only output @var{ast} for model @var{model}.

@item --parse-tree
@itemx -t
Instead of writing a full @var{ast}, write the @var{peg} parse tree.

@item --output=@var{file}
@itemx -o @var{file}
Write @var{ast} to @var{file}, use ``-'' for standard output.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn simulate
@section Invoking @command{dzn simulate}

The @command{dzn simulate} command starts a simulation run.

Under the hood, @command{dzn simulate} uses the Dezyne VM.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} simulate @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --no-deadlock
@itemx -D
Do not run the deadlock check.

@item --no-interface-determinism
Do not run the observable non-determinism check on interfaces.

@item --no-refusals
@itemx -R
Do not run the compliance check for the failures model refusals check.

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Print trace in format @var{format}; one of @code{diagram}, @code{event},
or @code{trace}.  The default is @code{trace}.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn simulate}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --internal
@itemx -i
Display internal events when using the @code{diagram} trace format.

@item --locations
@itemx -l
Display locations in the trace, this implies @option{--format=@code{trace}}.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Start simulating @var{model}.  The default is the most ``interesting''
model.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for simulation, the default is @code{3}.

@item --strict
@itemx -s
Use strict matching of trail, i.e., the trail must contain all
observable events.

@item --trail=@var{trail}
@itemx -t @var{trail}
Use trail @var{trail}.  The default is to read from @code{stdin}.

@item --verbose
@itemx -v
Display non-communication steps in the trace, this implies
@option{--format=@code{trace}}, @option{--locations}.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn trace
@section Invoking @command{dzn trace}

The @command{dzn trace} command is a pseudo-filter to translate between
different trace formats.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} trace @var{option}@dots{} [@file{FILE}]
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Display trace in format @var{format}, one of @code{diagram},
@code{event}, @code{json}, or @code{sexp}.  The default is @code{code}.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn trace}, and then exit.

@item --internal
Show communication between components in the system.  When using the
option @option{--format=diagram} on a system trace, the communication
between components in the system is hidden by default.

@item --locations
@itemx -L
Show locations in output.

@item --trail=@var{trail}
@itemx -t @var{trail}
Use trail @var{trail}.  The default is to read from standard input.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn traces
@section Invoking @command{dzn traces}

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}

The @command{dzn traces} command generates an exhaustive set of traces
for a behavioural Dezyne model.  It can also be used to generate an
@var{lts} in Aldebaran format (@xref{Invoking dzn lts}, @xref{Invoking
dzn explore}).

Under the hood, @command{dzn traces} uses @command{dzn code} and mCRL2.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} traces @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --flush
@itemx -f
Include @code{<flush>} events in trace.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn traces}, and then exit.

@item --illegal
@itemx -i
Include traces that lead to an illegal.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --lts
@itemx -l
Instead of generating trace files, generate an @var{lts} in Aldebaran
format.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate traces for model @var{model}.

@item --output=@var{dir}
@itemx -o @var{dir}
Write trace files to directory @var{dir}.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for generation, the default is @code{3}.

@item --traces
@itemx -t
Generate trace files, this is the default.  Using @option{--traces} will
generate trace files even when @option{--lts} is used.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn verify
@section Invoking @command{dzn verify}

The @command{dzn verify} command checks a Dezyne file for verification
errors in Dezyne models.  @xref{Verifying Models}.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} verify @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --all
@itemx -a
Show all errors, i.e., keep going after finding an error.  By default,
verification stops after finding a verification error.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn verify}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Limit verification to @var{model}, and for a behavioural component
model, to its interfaces.

@quotation Note
Verification cannot be limited to @code{system} component models;
verifying a system model is a no-op@footnote{The compositional property
of the Dezyne component-based programming paradigm guarantees that the
verification of a @code{system} component model amounts to the
verification of all its @code{interface} models and behavioral
@code{component} models.}.
@c XXX TODO: reference to compositional quality/property
@end quotation

@item --no-interface-determinism
Do not run the observable non-determinism check on interfaces.

@item --out=@var{format}
Run a partial verification pipeline to produce @var{format}.
Interesting formats are @code{mcrl2}, @code{aut},
@code{aut-dpweak-bisim}, @code{aut-weak-trace}, and
@code{aut+provides-aut}.  Use @option{--out=help} for a full list.

Using the @option{--debug} on @command{dzn} (@xref{Invoking dzn}) shows
the pipelines with all their commands that are being used, ready for
use on the command line.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for verification, the default is @code{3}.

@end table

