@node Identifiers
@section Identifiers
In Dezyne identifiers are used to denote objects like interfaces,
components, events, user defined types, variables, etc.  A keyword
cannot be used as an identifier and identifiers are case-sensitive.

An identifier starts with a letter, which can be followed by further
letters, digits, or underscores.  Following are legal identifiers:

Alarm, turn_on, VAL_123

@subsection Scoping
In order to properly refer to types and objects defined in a context
different from the current one, that context has to be included in the
name of such a type or object.  This is done using a 'dot notation',
like in @code{some_interface.enum_type}.  Possible dot constructs are:

@itemize

@item @code{enum_type.ENUM_FIELD} denotes an enumeration value,
where @code{enum_type} denotes its enumeration type defined in the current context.

@item @code{some_interface.enum_type} denotes an enumeration type defined in the
context of interface @code{some_interface}.

@item @code{some_interface.enum_type.ENUM_FIELD} denotes an enumeration value,
where @code{some_interface.enum_type} denotes its enumeration type defined in the
context of interface @code{some_interface}.

@item @code{some_port.some_event} denotes an event defined in the context of some
interface @code{some_interface} of which port @code{some_port} is an instance.

@item @code{some_instance.some_port} denotes a port defined in the context of some
component @code{some_component} of which @code{some_instance} is an instance.

@item @code{some_namespace.some_name} denotes an object named @code{some_name}, such as
a component, interface, enumeration value defined in a namespace @code{some_namespace}.
Since namespaces can be nested, long names can be constructed, like
@code{some_namespace1.some_namespace2.some_namespace2.some_interface.enum_type.ENUM_FIELD}.

@end itemize
Where appropriate in the sections below, examples will be given to illustrate this notation.
The following list shows the keywords in Dezyne.
These keywords may not be used as constant or variable or any other identifier names.

@example
behaviour       blocking        bool            component
else            extern          external        enum
false           if              illegal         import
inevitable      injected        inout           interface
in              namespace       on              optional
otherwise       out             provides        reply
requires        return          subint          system
true
@end example
Dezyne supports single-line and multi-line comments very similar to C++.
Multi-line comments may be nested.
All characters available inside any comment are ignored by the Dezyne compiler.

@example
component Alarm @{
  /* This is an example of multi-line comment.
   * The line below is ignored also:
   * interface IA
   */
  provides IAlarm ia; // a single-line comment
@}
@end example

