@node Dezyne Files
@section Dezyne Files
Dezyne components and interfaces are organized in files.  A file, with
extension '.dzn', contains a number of components and interfaces.

Components can refer to interfaces and other components.  An 'import'
clause is needed when the referred information is defined in another
file (see below).

The order of specification in one file is as follows:

@itemize

@item All necessary imports.
@item All interface and component definitions in arbitrary order.
@end itemize

@subsection Import
An @code{import} clause makes available all types, interfaces and
components that are defined in another file.  From an imported interface
or component the 'public' parts are available, i.e.  all information but
the interface or component behaviour, or the component system details.
Syntax:

@example
import file-name.dzn;
@end example

where @code{file-name.dzn} is a Dezyne file.

An imported file may contain imports itself, which are 'expanded' also.
When a file occurs twice in the resulting set of imports, it is expanded
only once.  This prevents the introduction of duplicate definitions.
Also recursive imports are handled correctly.

@cindex import
@cindex Files Syntax
@cindex file
@node Types and Expressions
@section Types and Expressions
In Dezyne all variables and constants are typed.
A number of type constructs are available.

@subsection Bool
@code{bool} is pre-defined and denotes the boolean type, with constants @code{true} and @code{false}.

Available boolean operators are:

@itemize

@item Logical negation, denoted by @code{! b1}.
@item Logical and, denoted by @code{b1 && b2}.
@item Logical or, denoted by @code{b1 || b2}.
@item Equality of two boolean expressions, denoted by @code{b1 == b2}.
@item Inequality of two boolean expressions, denoted by @code{b1 != b2}.
@end itemize
where @code{b1} and @code{b2} denote booleans.

@subsection Enum

An interface or component can specify a user defined enumerated
type.  Such a type has a name and a collection of values.  An example:

@example
  enum enum_type @{ value1, value2, value3 @};
@end example

where @code{enum} is a keyword; this defines the enum type @code{enum_type} with three values.

In expressions the enum values are referred to with a dot notation:
@code{enum_type.value2} .
Available enum operators are:

@itemize

@item Equality of two enum expressions, denoted by @code{e1 == e2}.
@item Inequality of two enum expressions, denoted by @code{e1 != e2}.
@item Testing the value of an enum variable, denoted by @code{v.value2}, which is shorthand for
@code{v == enum_type.value2}
@end itemize
where @code{e1} and @code{e2} denote enum expressions, and @code{v} an enum variable.

@subsection Subint

The integer type is available in Dezyne in a restricted way: only a
finite subset of integers can be used.  An explicit type definition is
needed for such a subset, where a C++-like syntax is used.  An example:

@example
  subint some_int_type @{2..5@};
@end example

where @code{subint} is a keyword.  This defines the finite type
@code{some_int_type} with possible values 2, 3, 4, and 5.  Available
integer operators are:

@itemize

@item A number of integer comparisons, denoted by:

@itemize

@item @code{i1}
@item @code{i1 <= i2}
@item @code{i1 >= i2}
@item @code{i1 >  i2}
@item @code{i1 == i2}
@item @code{i1 != i2}
@end itemize

@item Integer addition, denoted by @code{i1 + i2}.
@item Integer subtraction, denoted by @code{i1 - i2}.
@end itemize
where @code{i1} and @code{i2} denote integers.

@subsection Data Types

Apart from the @code{bool}, @code{enum}, and @code{int} types introduced
above, which play an important role in the description of interface and
component behaviour, so-called 'data types' can be defined.  These play a
restricted role and are used as types of 'data parameters' in events
(see below).  A data type is defined as follows:

@example
  extern some_data_type $some external type expression$;
@end example

where @code{extern} is a keyword, and in @code{$some external type
expression$} the dollar signs is a type expression in the target
language (C++, java, ...).

No Dezyne supported expressions are available for data types, apart from
'dollar expressions': @code{$some expression$} will be passed as-is.

