@node Interface Models
@section Interface Models
An interface has a name, can define some local types, defines a collection of events,
and a behaviour describing the protocol on its events.
A syntax example:

@example
interface some_interface
@{
  enum enum_type @{ Val1, Val2, Val3 @};
  extern some_string $std::string$;
  in enum_type valued_event(some_string s);
  out void reply_event();
  behaviour
  @{
    on valued_event(s) : @{ reply enum_type.Val3; @}
  @}
@}
@end example

In this example a number of keywords are introduced:
@code{interface}, @code{in}, @code{out},
@code{void}, @code{behaviour}, @code{on}, and @code{reply}.

The example defines an interface named @code{some_interface} with two local types,
two events, and the interface behaviour  (see below for a syntax description of events and behaviour).

@subsection Events
An event has (in this order):

@itemize

@item a direction (@code{in} or @code{out}),
@item optionally a reply type (@code{void} if it is absent),
@item a user defined name,
@item a data parameter list, which may be empty.

@end itemize
Some examples:

@example
  in void e2();            // a void in event called 'e2' with an empty parameter list
  in enum_type e3();      // a valued in event called 'e3'
  out void e4(some_string s); // a void out event called 'e4' with one data parameter
@end example

There is a restriction on event definitions: an @code{out} event must be @code{void}.

@subsection Behaviour
The @code{behaviour} section of an interface contains the protocol description of the interface.
@xref{Interface and Component Behaviour}, for an elaborate description.

@cindex type
@cindex Interfaces Syntax
@cindex protocol
@cindex interface
@cindex event
@cindex data
@node Component Models
@section Component Models

A component has a name, a collection of ports by which it communicates
with the outside world, and optionally a description of its internals.
A syntax example:

@example
component some_component
@{
  provides some_interface1 some_port1;
  requires some_interface2 some_port2;
  requires some_interface3 some_port3;
  /*
   * internals description....
   */
@}
@end example

In this example a number of keywords are introduced:
@code{component}, @code{provides}, and @code{requires}.

The example defines a component named @code{some_component} with three ports.

@subsection Ports

A component provides some functionality, and requires functionality of
other components.  Communication between components is performed through
their ports, which are instances of interfaces.  Each port has a
direction according to its intention (@code{provides} or
@code{requires}), the interface it implements and a local name.  A
component refers to these ports in its behaviour.

@subsubsection Injection
A @code{requires} port can be specified to be @code{injected}:

@example
  requires injected some_interface some_port;
@end example

The intention is, that binding such a port will occur at a high level in the system hierarchy
to some component port @code{someComponent.somePort}, and that more than one injected port can be bound to that port.
For that reason @code{some_interface} cannot define @code{out} events.

@xref{System Components} for a detailed description of the binding of injected ports.

@subsection Internal Description
The component's internal description comes in three flavors:

@itemize

@item
Behavioural: Like in the interface protocol the internals are given as a
behavioural description, in which for each event the required actions
are given.  @xref{Interface and Component Behaviour}.

@item
Compositional: The functionality is described as the composition of a
number of sub components.  @xref{System Components}.

@item
Hand-written: The internals are missing indicating the intention to have
a hand-written implementation of the component.  This implementation
must be such that it satisfies the specified ports.  The component
is a place-holder only.

@end itemize

