@node Interface and Component Behaviour
@section Interface and Component Behaviour

A behaviour description might look like this:

@example
behaviour
@{
  enum enum_type @{ value1, value2 @};
  type enum_var = enum_type.value1;
  bool bool_var = true;
  on some_port1.some_event1():
  @{
    bool blocal = bool_var;
    bool_var = false;
    some_port2.some_event2();
    f(blocal);
  @}
  [enum_var.value2]
  @{
    on some_port1.some_event2(): illegal;
  @}
  void f(bool b)
  @{
    if (b) some_port2.some_event5();
    else @{ some_port2.some_event5(); bool_var = true; @}
  @}
@}
@end example

This behaviour section introduces a local enum type (@code{enum_type}),
two variables (called @code{enum_var} and @code{bool_var}),
a number of statements, and a function definition (@code{void f(bool b)}) with one parameter.
Note that in a sub scope a local variable @code{blocal} is defined.
The different constructs are handled in more detail below.

@subsection Variable Definitions

As demonstrated in the example above, variables can be defined in a
behaviour description, both at top level and in a local scope.  Variables
must be given an initial value.

The member variables are often referred to as 'state variables'.
Their scope extends to the complete behaviour description, including the
body of functions defined in the behaviour.

Variables defined at other places have a scope which is restricted to the @code{compound}
(@code{@{ ....  @}}) they are defined in.

@subsubsection Member Variables

@subsection Declarative versus Imperative Statements

There are two 'kinds' of behavioural statements: 'declarative' and
'imperative'.  The declarative part describes the trigger events and the
conditions in which they have to be handled, while the imperative part
describes the response that has to occur as result of a trigger.

@subsection @code{compound}
Statements of the same 'kind' can be grouped using curly braces:

@example
  @{ Statement1; Statement2; Statement3; @}
@end example

It results in a single '@code{compound}', of the same 'kind' as its
sub statements, and can be used as such.
Note that the list of statements within the curly braces can be empty:

@example
  @{ /* this is an empty statement sequence */ @}
@end example

@subsection Declarative Statements
The triggers an interface or component has to handle and the conditions
in which they occur are described as declarative statements.
The conditions are expressed as @code{guard}s, the triggers as
@code{on}s.

@subsubsection @code{guard}
A @code{guard} looks like:

@example
  [ bool-expression ] statement
@end example

The square brackets (@code{[} and @code{]}) must contain a boolean expression
expressing the validity of the guard.  The statement following the guard can be either
declarative or imperative.

@subsubsection @code{on}
In an interface behaviour specification an @code{on} is expressed as:

@example
  on some_event: statement
@end example

The statement contains a keyword @code{on}, the name of an event
introduced in the interface, a colon (@code{:}), and a statement,
which can be either be declarative or imperative.
A declarative statement must not contain further @code{on}s:
nesting these statements is not allowed.

Note that no event parameters must be specified in an interface.

In a component behaviour specification an @code{on} is expressed as:

@example
  on some_port.some_event(param1): statement
@end example

where @code{some_port} is a port of the component with an interface type
that contains event @code{some_event} with one data parameter.  Note
that in a component behaviour specification data parameters have to be
used where specified.  On the trigger each data parameter must be a
fresh variable, implicitly typed conform the event specification.

@subsection Imperative Statements
The response on a (guarded) trigger event are expressed in the
imperative statement following the declarative part.  All variable
assignments, event actions, function calls, etc.  are handled here.

@subsubsection Variable Definition
New variables can be declared as follows:

@example
  some_type some_variable = initial_value_expression;
@end example

where @code{some_type} denotes a previously defined type,
@code{some_variable} is a 'fresh' name, and
@code{initial_value_expression} an expression of type
@code{some_type}.

After the variable has been declared it can be referred to as long as the
referring place is in scope (scopes being introduced by compounds).
'Fresh' should be interpreted as follows:

@itemize

@item No two variables with the same name can be declared in one scope.
@item A variable @code{some_variable} that has been declared in a wider scope
can be 'shadowed' by a variable definition with the same name in a sub scope
@end itemize

@subsubsection @code{assign}
A previously declared variable can change value using an @code{assign}:

@example
  some_variable = value_expression;
@end example

@subsubsection Action Statement
In handling the response on a trigger event, an event action can be called.
The syntax in an interface definition is:

@example
  some_event;
@end example

where @code{some_event} is the name of an out event introduced in the interface.
Note that no event parameters must be specified.

In a component behaviour specification an action statement is expressed as:

@example
  some_port.some_event(parameter_expression);
@end example

where @code{some_port} is a port of the component with an interface type
that contains event @code{some_event} with one data parameter.

Note that the event in an action statement must be a void event.  For a
valued event the return value must be caught, a variable definition or
an @code{assign} are the appropriate ways to handle that:

@example
  bool b = r.bool_event ();
  @dots{}
  b = r.bool_event2 ();
@end example

or used in a simple expression, possibly using @b{==}, @b{!=}, @b{!}, @b{&&}, @b{||}
(since v2.14)

@example
  if (r.bool_event ()) ...;
  if (!r.bool_event ()) ...;
  if (!r.bool_event () && b) ...;
  if (r.enum_event () == Enum.OK) ...;
  if (r.enum_event () != Enum.OK || b) ...;
  reply (r.enum_event ());
  reply (r.enum_event () != Enum.FAIL);
@end example

@subsubsection Function @code{call}
A function defined in a behavioral specification can be called with
properly typed parameter expressions.  Given a function definition

@example
  void some_function(enum_type e, bool b) @{ /* ...  */ @}
@end example

a function @code{call} might look like:

@example
  some_function(enum-expression, bool-expression);
@end example

Note that the function in a function @code{call} must be a void
function.  For a valued function the return value must be caught, a a
variable definition or an @code{assign} are the appropriate ways
to handle that:

@example
  bool b = bool_function ();
  @dots{}
  b = bool_function ();
@end example

or used in a simple expression, possibly using @b{==}, @b{!=} or @b{!}
(since v2.14)

@example
  if (bool_function ()) ...;
  if (!bool_function ()) ...;
  if (enum_function () == Enum.OK) ...;
  reply (enum_function ());
@end example

@subsubsection @code{reply}
A valued trigger event will have to set the appropriate return value in
its response handling.  Setting that value (not returning yet) is denoted as:

@example
  reply(valued_expression);
@end example

@subsubsection @code{return}
A valued function has to return with a value of the appropriate type.
This looks like:

@example
  return valued_expression;
@end example

@subsubsection @code{if}
Conditional handling of statements is supported by the @code{if},
which can have an optional else part:

@example
  if (bool-expression) statement1
@end example

or:

@example
  if (bool-expression) then-statement else else-statement
@end example

where @code{if} and @code{else} are keywords, and the parentheses are
part of the construct.

@noindent
The @code{bool-expression} between the
parentheses must be a simple boolean expression and may contain only one
unconditional @code{call} or @code{action} (since 2.14).

@noindent
The statements @code{then-statement} and @code{else-statement} are
arbitrary imperative statements.

Note that nested @code{if}s are allowed, and that

@example
  if (b1) if (b2) then-statement else else-statement
@end example

will be interpreted as

@example
  if (b1)
  @{ if (b2) then-statement else else-statement @}
@end example

and not as

@example
  if (b1)
  @{ if (b2) then-statement @}
  else else-statement
@end example

In other words: @code{else} binds to the closest if.

@subsection Functions

A function definition introduces the signature of a function and its
body.  The signature is built up from the return type, the name of the
function, and a list of typed parameters.  The body is a @code{compound}
in the imperative part of the language, so no on-event and @code{guard}s
are allowed.  It is allowed however to refer to action events and member
variables, and of course to the function parameters.

An example:

@example
bool some_function(bool param1, some_enum param2)
@{
  bool b = param2;
  if (param1)
  @{
    some_port.some_event();
    b = false;
  @}
  member_var = param2;
  other_function(b);
  return true;
@}
@end example

This declares a function called @code{some_function} with two parameters
(of type @code{bool} and @code{some_enum} respectively) and returning a
value of type @code{bool}.  In the function body a local variable is
declared, a conditional action event is called, a member variable
is set, another function is called, and the return value is set.

Functions are allowed to be recursive, and also mutual recursive
(function @code{f}calling function @code{g} and vice versa), under one
condition: A recursive function must be "tail recursive"; this means
that the recursive call must be the last statement in the function.  The
rationale for this restriction comes from the need for verification: the
generic recursive case cannot be verified.

