@node System Components
@section System Components

A component which is composed from a number of sub components has a
'system' internal description.  This description specifies the available
sub component instances, and all connections between the component
ports.  An example: suppose the following components to be defined:

@example
component foo @{
  provides ifoo f;
  requires ibar b;
  requires inut n;
  //  ...  internals ...
@}
component bar @{
  provides ibar b;
  // ...  internals ...
@}
component nut @{
  provides inut n;
  requires iwell w;
  // ...  internals ...
@}
@end example

Then a system component @code{sys} could be defined:

@example
component sys @{
  provides ifoo top;
  requires iwell bot;
  // ...  internals ...
@}
@end example

where its internals are composed of the @code{foo}, @code{bar}, and
@code{nut} components:

@example
component sys @{
  provides ifoo top;
  requires iwell bot;
  system @{
    foo cfoo;
    bar cbar;
    nut cnut;
    top <=> cfoo.f;
    cfoo.b <=> cbar.b;
    cfoo.n <=> cnut.n;
    cnut.w <=> bot;
  @}
@}
@end example

The system description shows the instantiation of the three sub
components, and four connections between various ports.

@subsection Component Instances
In a system description a sub component is specified by its type and
local name:

@example
  some_component some_instance;
@end example

The definition of some_component has to be available, potentially through
an 'import'.

It is allowed to have more than one instance of the same type:

@example
  some_component some_instance1;
  some_component some_instance2;
@end example

@subsection Binding
Communication between components is achieved through component ports.
Communication is specified as binding:

@example
  some_component1.port1 <=> some_component2.port2;
@end example

indicates components @code{some_component1} and @code{some_component2}communicate
through their respective ports @code{port1}and @code{port2}.  This is
often expressed as: @code{port1} is bound to @code{port2}.

Binding is symmetric: @code{some_component1.port1 <=> some_component2.port2}and
@code{some_component2.port2 <=> some_component1.port1} have identical meaning.

Communication is restricted to ports of the same (interface) type.
Moreover communication 'direction' has to be preserved.  There are two
cases:

@itemize

@item Two sub components communicating: always a @code{provides} port binds to
a @code{requires} port, like in @code{cfoo.bar <=> cbar.b}in the example
above.

@item Port forwarding (an external port is forwarded to a sub-component port):
always the directions have to be the same, like in @code{top <=>
cfoo.foo}and @code{cnut.wl <=> bot} in the example above.

@end itemize

@subsubsection Injection
Binding of @code{injected} ports is done at a higher system level
(@pxref{Component Models}).  A wild-card character (@code{*}) is used to
achieve the binding of one @code{provides} port to all @code{injected
requires} ports.

Let's take a typical example involving logging:

@example
interface ilog @{
  ...
@}
component logger @{
  provides ilog log;
  ...
@}
@end example

Suppose a lot of components require logging:

@example
...
component some_component12 @{
  provides some_interface12 p;
  requires injected ilog l;
  ...
@}
component some_component13 @{
  provides some_interface13 p;
  requires injected ilog l;
  ...
@}
...
@end example

then some system component can bind all logging in one go:

@example
component some_system @{
  ...
  system @{
    logger clog;
    ...
    some_component12 c12;
    some_component13 c13;
    ...
    clog.log <=> *;
  @}
@}
@end example

It is allowed to group some components in a sub system:

@example
component some_sub_system @{
  ...
  system @{
    ...
    some_component12 c12;
    some_component13 c13;
    ...
  @}
@}
@end example

and do the wild-card binding for that sub system only:

@example
component some_system @{
  ...
  system @{
    logger clog;
    some_sub_system subsys;
    ...
    clog.log <=> subsys.*;
  @}
@}
@end example

