@node Namespaces
@section Namespaces

All component, interface, and type definitions can be defined in a
@i{namespace}, which provides name scoping.  The scope can be used when
referring to such a definition.

@subsection Namespace Syntax

A namespace has a name, and within its scope components, interfaces,
types, and sub-namespaces can be defined.

A syntax example:

@example
namespace some_namespace @{
  extern some_string $std::string$;
  interface some_interface @{
    enum enum_type @{ val1, val2, val3 @};
    in enum_type valued_event(some_string s);
    out void reply_event();
    behaviour @{
      on valued_event(s) : @{ reply enum_type.val3; @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

In this example namespace @code{some_namespace} is introduced.  In its scope
data type @code{some_string} and interface @code{some_interface}are defined.

An example with nested namespaces introduces namespace
@code{some_namespace1}, and within that (among others) namespace
@code{some_namespace2}, which itself contains interface @code{some_interface}:

@example
namespace some_namespace1 @{
  extern some_string $std::string$;
  namespace some_namespace2 @{
    interface some_interface @{
      enum enum_type @{ val1, val2, val3 @};
      in type valued_event(some_string s);
      out void reply_event();
      behaviour @{
         on valued_event(s) : @{ reply type.val3; @}
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection Namespace Re-definition
It is allowed to spread the definition of types, interfaces, components,
and sub-namespaces over multiple instances of a namespace scope.  This is
most useful since in a 'real' project definitions are spread over
multiple files.

So

@example
namespace some_namespace1 @{
  extern some_string $std::string$;
  interface some_interface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example

is equivalent to

@example
namespace some_namespace1 @{
  extern some_string $std::string$;
@}
namespace some_namespace1 @{
  interface some_interface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example

@subsection Referencing
When within namespace @code{some_namespace} @code{some_type} is defined, then
outside that namespace it is referred to by prefixing it with the name
of that namespace and a dot, as in: @code{some_namespace.some_type}

Within its own namespace the short name @code{some_type} is to be used.

In complex cases it may be necessary to refer to the @i{global}
namespace which has an empty name; this results in name references
starting with a dot, as can be seen in the following somewhat convoluted
example.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/inner-space.dzn
@end example

which defines:

@itemize

@item interface @code{foo.I} with local enum @code{foo.I.Bool}
@item interface @code{inner.foo.I} with local enum @code{inner.foo.I.Bool}
@item component @code{inner.space}
@item component @code{bar.c}
@end itemize

The two variables defined in component @code{inner.space} have types
@code{foo.I.Bool} and @code{.foo.I.Bool} respectively.  The first type
expands to @code{inner.foo.I.Bool} since it is defined in namespace
@code{inner}.  The starting dot in the second definition prevents this
expansion.

@subsection Shorthand Namespace Syntax
In trivial cases, e.g.  where only one definition is provided within a
namespace, a dot notation can be used.  Using this notation,

@example
namespace some_namespace1 @{
  namespace some_namespace2 @{
    extern some_string $std::string$;
  @}
  interface some_interface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example

can be written as:

@example
extern some_namespace1.some_namespace2.some_string $std::string$;
interface some_namespace1.some_interface @{ ...  @}
@end example

